[start section id="20112"]

#1 Rectal cancer
Discussed in-depth in Mrs. Camara and her son the evaluation of rectal cancer.  We will start with an endoscopic rectal ultrasound.  We will attempt another colonoscopy as she has not had evaluation of her proximal colon, although I discussed with her this may or may not be able to be performed.  We will have this tattooed.  If the EUS reveals this is located above 10-cm, we will need to obtain a pelvic MRI to assess the mesorectal radial margin so I will tentatively schedule a pelvic MRI.  I discussed with her if we cannot complete the full colonoscopy, there is a chance she may need a CT colonography or hypaque enema, but I will not schedule these at this time.  Discussed she may need neoadjuvant therapy with chemotherapy and radiation based on the test results.  I will see her back with Dr. Hollister later this week following her testing.  She will be going to Enema Prep before her appointment with Dr. Hollister so he can perform a proctoscopy.  We will get a chest x-ray, CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis, as well as CEA for staging.  Discussed with Mrs. Camara that her children need to undergo colonoscopies starting at age 50.  However, I discussed with her son who accompanies her, as he had polyps at 20, he will need to get those records and discuss with his primary-care provider when it would be appropriate for his children to undergo screening.
#2 Fecal seepage
I have some concerns, even if she has a high rectal cancer, about her having incontinence problems.  I will get a baseline anorectal manometry testing for evaluation.
#3 Accelerated hypertension
This may be whitecoat hypertension.  She just took her antihypertensives in my office.  I will see her back this afternoon to recheck her blood pressure.  If this continues to be elevated, it may be important for us to get six-hour blood pressure monitoring.
#4 PAME
As she has risk factors for coronary artery disease including hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, obesity, being over age 65 and as she has a low functional status and we cannot have her exercise to see what her tolerance is, we will need to proceed with pharmacological dobutamine stress echocardiogram testing. We will get a baseline EKG first.  This will also evaluate her valves as she has this murmur and lower-extremity edema which may be concerning for congestive heart failure.  I have discussed with her to hold her vitamin E and fish oil at this time during her evaluation.
#5 Glaucoma
Stable.
#6 Obesity
I am not sure whether or not she will be a laparoscopic candidate.
Spent 90 minutes with Mrs. Camara and her son reviewing the plan of care in detail.
Separately, as she has had problems with contrast dye in the past, I will premedicate her with Medrol 12 hours and 2 hours before her CT-scan so as to minimize the risk of a reaction. I do think we should try our best to try to get a CT-scan with contrast if our radiologists feel that this is appropriate for staging.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will:  She asked me to discuss with her the details of what an advance directive is which I did and gave her information.
Code status:  Discussed with Mrs. Camara.  She would like to be a full code.

