[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Camara is a 77-year-old female from Owens Cross Roads Tampa with a six-month history of a change in her bowel habits. Until January 2009 she had really not been to a healthcare provider for many years as she felt she was healthy. She had no prior history of a colonoscopy or other healthcare maintenance care.  She actually went in for evaluation in 2009 as she did not feel well and was found to have severely elevated blood pressure, over 200 systolic, and then began being followed regularly for her blood pressure by a local physician assistant.
In March she went in for evaluation as she developed worsening constipation.  She started taking Benefiber without relief.  She also developed rectal bleeding which had been going on for about a month with bowel movements, and she had a larger episode in March which led her to go in for evaluation of the bleeding.  A digital rectal exam was performed, and there was blood on the glove, and it was recommended she get a diagnostic colonoscopy which was performed on April 9, 2010, by Dr. Bouknight.  A complete colonoscopy was unable to be performed as she was found to have a nearly-obstructing mass located approximately 10-cm from the anal verge. This was biopsied with pathology reviewed here revealing invasive, grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.  This has not yet been tattooed.  She has no family history of colorectal cancer. She has not had obstructive symptoms. She denies abdominal pain, significant weight-loss, or fatigue. Dr. Bouknight had her start on MiraLAX once-a-day following her colonoscopy which she has been taking, and she has generally been moving her bowels twice-a-day on the medication.  She has not had bleeding since her colonoscopy on April 9th.  She has not had further evaluation for her cancer.  She denies true fecal incontinence.  However, she mentions she has been having some leakage since she has been on the MiraLAX , mostly mucus and occasional brown staining on her underwear.  Prior to the last few months, she had not had leakage problems.
Separately, she informs me she has a cystocele.  She attributes this to occurring after a previous gynecological exam, and she is interested in getting a pessary.  At times the bulge protrudes through the vaginal introitus and is bothersome, but it does not come out with general activities such as walking.  She is mostly here for her rectal cancer but brought this up as well but after further discussion she decided she will see someone locally about a pessary.  She denies urinary incontinence, a history of urinary tract infections, and hematuria.

